<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF APPEAL</TI>
<P>TAKE NOTICE THAT the Squamish Nation (also known as the Squamish Indian Band) and x&ag;lek/se<UNDER>k</UNDER>y&ua; si&yuml;am, Chief Ian Campbell on his own behalf and on behalf of all members of the Squamish Nation hereby appeal to the Court of Appeal for British Columbia from the order of The Honourable Mr. Justice Grauer of the Supreme Court of British Columbia pronounced the 24<SUP>th</SUP> day of May, 2018, at Vancouver, British Columbia.</P>
<P>1. The appeal is from a:
<P1>[X] Trial Judgment</P1></P>
<P>2. If the appeal is from an appeal under Rule 49 or 53(6) of the Supreme Court Rules, name the maker of the original decision, direction or order:</P>
<P>3. Please identify which of the following is involved in the appeal
<P1>[X] Constitutional/Administrative</P1>
<P1>[ ] Civil Procedure</P1>
<P1>[ ] Commercial</P1>
<P1>[ ] Motor Vehicle Accidents</P1>
<P1>[ ] Municipal Law</P1>
<P1>[ ] Real Property</P1>
<P1>[ ] Torts</P1>
<P1>[ ] Equity</P1>
<P1>[ ] Wills and Estates</P1></P>
<P>And further take notice that the Court of Appeal will be moved at the hearing of this application for
<P1>1. An order that the appeal be allowed and that the Order of Mr. Justice Grauer made May 24, 2018 be set aside;</P1>
<P1>2. An order quashing or setting aside the decision of the Minister of Environment and Minister of Natural Gas Development (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Ministers</BOLD>&rdquo;) under s. 17(3)(c) of the <EM>Environmental Assessment Act</EM>, S.B.C. 2002, c. 43 (the &ldquo;Act&rdquo;) to issue an Environmental Assessment Certificate (&ldquo;<BOLD>EAC</BOLD>&rdquo;) for the Trans Mountain Expansion Project (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Project</BOLD>&rdquo;) on January 10, 2017 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Decision</BOLD>&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>3. A declaration that the Crown in right of the Province of British Columbia (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Province</BOLD>&rdquo;) owes a duty to consult and accommodate the petitioners with respect to the subject matter of the Decision, prior to the Decision by the Ministers;</P1>
<P1>4. A declaration that the Province has not met its constitutional duty to consult and accommodate the petitioners with respect to the subject matter of the Decision;</P1>
<P1>5. A declaration that the Ministers lacked the lawful authority to make the Decision in breach of the Province's legal and constitutional obligations to the petitioners and the Decision is therefore invalid;</P1>
<P1>6. A declaration that unless and until a valid EAC is issued in respect of the Project a minister, or employee or agent of the provincial government, is prohibited from issuing, in relation to the Project, an approval under any other provincial enactment and any such approval is without effect.</P1>
<P1>7. Costs in this Court and in the Court below; and</P1>
<P1>8. Such further relief as this Honourable Court may consider just.</P1></P>
<P>The trial/hearing of this proceeding occupied 4 days.</P>
<P>Dated at North Vancouver, British Columbia, this 20<SUP>th</SUP> day of June, 2018.</P>
