<TBLBODY TBLWD="600">
<TBLCDEFS COLSEP="VSINGLE" HALIGN="LEFT" CHARPOS="75%" TOPSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCDEF COLWD="25" TBLUNITS="PERCENT">
<TBLCDEF COLWD="75" TBLUNITS="PERCENT">
</TBLCDEFS>
<TBLROWS ROWSEP="HDOT" VALIGN="TOP" LEFTSEP="VSINGLE">
<?TBLROW 1>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">June 21, 2010</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The National Energy Board (&ldquo;<BOLD>NEB</BOLD>&rdquo;) and British Columbia (&ldquo;<BOLD>BC</BOLD>&rdquo;) Environmental Assessment Office (&ldquo;<BOLD>EAO</BOLD>&rdquo;) entered into an Equivalency Agreement under which the EAO accepts NEB assessments as equivalent for projects that trigger both EAO and NEB reviews.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 2>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 3>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">December 14, 2011</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">Trans Mountain Pipeline ULC (&ldquo;<BOLD>TM</BOLD>&rdquo;) began its efforts to engage and consult with Squamish Nation (&ldquo;<BOLD>Squamish</BOLD>&rdquo;) regarding the Trans Mountain Expansion Project (&ldquo;<BOLD>Project</BOLD>&rdquo;).</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 4>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 5>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">December 16, 2013</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">TM submitted its 15,000 page Project application to the NEB.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 6>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 7>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">April 2, 2014</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The NEB: (1) granted participation status to 400 intervenors and 1,250 commenters, including Squamish and the Province of British Columbia (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Province</BOLD>&rdquo;); (2) issued a Hearing Order setting out events, steps and deadlines; (3) determined that TM's application was complete; and, (4) determined the scope of its environmental assessment (&ldquo;<BOLD>EA</BOLD>&rdquo;), noting that Project-related marine shipping would be considered under the <EM>National Energy Board Act</EM>, R.S.C., 1985, c. N-7 (&ldquo;<BOLD>NEB Act</BOLD>&rdquo;) and cumulative effects analysis under the <EM>Canadian Environmental Assessment Act</EM>, 2012, S.C. 2012, c. 19, s. 52 (&ldquo;<BOLD>CEAA 2012</BOLD>&rdquo;).</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 8>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 9>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">December 11, 2014</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">Transport Canada (&ldquo;<BOLD>TC</BOLD>&rdquo;) issued the Technical Review Process of Marine Terminal Systems and Transhipment Sites (&ldquo;<BOLD>TERMPOL</BOLD>&rdquo;) report, which made 17 recommendations and 31 findings regarding Project-related marine shipping safety.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 10>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 11>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">January 15, 2015</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The NEB issued Ruling No. 50 denying the Province's motion to require TM file un-redacted and additional emergency management program (&ldquo;<BOLD>EMP</BOLD>&rdquo;) information and documents. The NEB noted that it had &ldquo;sufficient information&rdquo; to meet its filing requirements and that consultation with the Province, including disclosure, would occur in the future.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 12>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 13>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">January 13, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The Supreme Court of British Columbia issued Reasons for Judgment in <EM>Coastal First Nations v. British Columbia (Environment)</EM>, 2016 BCSC 34 (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Coastal First Nations</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;). The Court found that, among other things, BC cannot refuse to issue an Environmental Assessment Certificate (&ldquo;<BOLD>EAC</BOLD>&rdquo;) for an interprovincial pipeline but has the power to impose conditions on areas of provincial jurisdiction subject to the constitutional doctrines of interjurisdictional immunity and federal paramountcy.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 14>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 15>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">January 27, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The Federal Government introduced Interim Measures for Pipeline Reviews. For the Project this included deeper consultations with Indigenous groups, an upstream greenhouse gas assessment and a three-member ministerial panel to engage local and Indigenous communities.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 16>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 17>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">April 1, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The EAO informed Squamish that it would consult on &ldquo;areas of provincial jurisdiction&rdquo;.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 18>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 19>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">April 8, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The EAO ordered that the Project requires an EAC.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 20>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 21>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">May 9, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The EAO requested Squamish's comments on proposed procedures for the EAO assessment, including consultation on issues of &ldquo;provincial jurisdiction&rdquo;. Additionally, the EAO explained TM's role in the consultation process.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 22>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 23>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">May 18, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">TM provided to Squamish a draft Aboriginal Engagement Report.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 24>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 25>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">May 19, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The NEB released its report (&ldquo;<BOLD>NEB Report</BOLD>&rdquo;) recommending the Governor in Council (&ldquo;<BOLD>GIC</BOLD>&rdquo;) approve the Project in the Canadian public interest, subject to 157 conditions (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Federal Conditions</BOLD>&rdquo;).</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 26>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 27>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">May 24, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">Squamish wrote to the EAO regarding the Project, requesting that the EAO terminate the Equivalency Agreement and subject the Project to a full EAO assessment.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 28>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 29>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">June 2, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The EAO wrote to Squamish regarding the Project, explaining processes by which it would assess the Project short of terminating the Equivalency Agreement.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 30>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 31>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">June 17, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">In its &ldquo;<BOLD>S. 11 Order</BOLD>&rdquo; the EAO accepted the NEB assessment as equivalent and established the scope, procedures and methods for the EAO review, noting that it would consult identified Indigenous groups on issues of &ldquo;provincial jurisdiction&rdquo;.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 32>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 33>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">June 17, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The EAO offered Squamish $5,000 in funding to participate in the EAO review process. Squamish did not respond.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 34>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 35>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">June 19, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">Canada's <EM>Pipeline Safety Act</EM> came into force, imposing new requirements on pipeline operators.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 36>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 37>
<TBLROW>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">June 23, 2016</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2">The EAO met with Squamish and Tsleil-Waututh Nation (&ldquo;<BOLD>TWN</BOLD>&rdquo;) to discuss the Project.</TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 38>
<TBLROW ROWSEP="HSINGLE">
<TBLCELL COLSTART="1">&newline;</TBLCELL>
<TBLCELL COLSTART="2"></TBLCELL>
</TBLROW>
<?TBLROW 39>
