<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, Christopher Gardner, of Unit XXXXXXXXXX AFFIRM THAT:</P>
<P>1. I am the President of the Independent Contractors and Businesses Association (the &ldquo;<BOLD>ICBA</BOLD>&rdquo;) and as such have personal knowledge of the facts and matters to which I depose in this affidavit. If any knowledge is stated to be based on my information and belief, I verily believe it to be true.</P>
<P>2. I have been the President of the ICBA since February, 2017. My responsibilities at the ICBA include leading the ICBA's public policy advocacy initiatives related to major construction projects, responsible resource development, and employment and work place regulation; representing the ICBA in meetings with federal, provincial and municipal government officials; and leading the ICBA's senior management team as it builds its training and benefits business.</P>
<P>3. Before joining the ICBA, I was Senior Vice President of Civeo Corporation, one of the largest providers of workforce accommodations (work camps), remote catering services and logistics in North America. The clients of Civeo include large energy and construction companies and their subcontractor companies performing work in remote locations. I was also Executive Vice President of Britco, the largest modular construction company in British Columbia. Britco designs and builds both temporary and permanent workforce accommodations for companies developing and constructing projects throughout Western Canada in the energy and resource development sectors.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Background to the ICBA</TI>
<P>4. The ICBA is a voluntary association of construction businesses in British Columbia, representing more than 2,000 companies and clients across the Province, including over 1,000 construction companies.</P>
<P>5. The ICBA was formed in 1975 as an organization to represent and advocate for the interests of open shop contractors, who at that time were routinely denied work on government projects on the basis that its workers were not unionized with the politically powerful Building Trades Unions.</P>
<P>6. The ICBA continues to advocate on behalf of free enterprise and the principle of open and fair bidding for projects, without discrimination on the basis of an employer's association with specific unions.</P>
<P>7. Our position is that economic development brings a range of advantages to British Columbia, including economic prosperity, greater tax revenues to pay for public services, a higher standard of living, and greater employment opportunities for members of the community.</P>
<P>8. The ICBA's mission is to foster and perpetuate the principle of open shop contracting, and to support the success of members through the provision of value added services.</P>
<P>9. To that end, the ICBA engages in various public policy and lobbying activities relating to legislation and government programs involving labour relations, employment standards, apprenticeship training, worker's compensation, safety, and unemployment insurance.</P>
<P>10. It also engages in public advocacy on issues that impact its members, including labour and employment policies, fair tendering, Worksafe BC policies, regulation and taxation, infrastructure, responsible resource development, and generally promoting economic development in the public interest.</P>
<P>11. The ICBA also provides services to its membership, including assistance with arranging various services, including access to health and retirement plans, construction market information, apprenticeship support and management training, and affinity programs that provide discounts on hotels, gas, and other goods and services.</P>
<P>12. The ICBA is also the single largest sponsor of construction apprentices in BC and trains over 3,000 construction professionals annually.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>ICBA's Interest in the Trans Mountain Expansion Project</TI>
<P>13. Publicly available documents show that, in late 2016, Kinder Morgan Canada obtained regulatory approval from the federal government to proceed with the Trans Mountain Expansion Project (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Project</BOLD>&rdquo;), an estimated $7.4 billion expansion of the existing Trans Mountain Pipeline system.</P>
<P>14. Subsequently, in January of 2017, the provincial government issued a certificate under provincial legislation approving the Project, which is the approval at issue in this appeal.</P>
<P>15. I understand that the Project includes upgrades to facilities in and around Edmonton; an expansion of the pipeline and associated facilities between Edmonton and Burnaby (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Pipeline</BOLD>&rdquo;); and the construction of three new births at the Westridge Marine Terminal.</P>
<P>16. According to the Trans Mountain project's website, the Pipeline expansion elements of the Project are divided into seven distinct segments across Alberta and British Columbia, with the five British Columbia spreads expected to be contracted to a number of primary contractors.</P>
<P>17. A number of large ICBA construction contractors are expected to bid on contracts to work on various aspects of the Project.</P>
<P>18. It is also common in projects of this magnitude for primary contractors to contract with various subcontractors to perform work related to site preparation, clearing, and grading; transportation of materials to site; on-site staging of equipment; workforce accommodation and catering; power generation; design and engineering services&mdash;civil, structural and environmental; site security; and equipment rental.</P>
<P>19. Therefore, many ICBA member organizations have been or will be seeking contracts or subcontracts to work on the Project, given the enormous size of the Project and the prevalence of ICBA members as key construction industry participants in every region of the province.</P>
<P>20. According to recent Conference Board of Canada reports, the Project is expected to be massive in scale, and to have significant economic benefits to British Columbia and its workforce.</P>
<P>21. With respect to the initial construction of the pipeline and related infrastructure, and based on a projected capital cost of $5.4 billion, the Conference Board estimated in 2014 that the Project will create 58,037 person-years of employment. It also estimated that the Project will employ approximately 13,500 employees at the peak of the construction phase, and that it is expected to generate a total of $1.2 billion in federal ($646 million) and provincial ($568 million) government revenues, with the majority of those benefits accruing in British Columbia. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of that June 2014 Conference Board Report.</P>
<P>22. More recently, the Conference Board further estimates that the overall economic benefits of the Project will be much greater; 802,000 person-years of employment and $46.7 billion in government revenues over a twenty-five year period (between 2012 and 2038), much of which will accrue directly to businesses, employees, and governments in British Columbia. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of that December 2015 Conference Board Report.</P>
<P>23. Therefore, the Project is expected to make up a sizable share of economic and employment opportunities in the Province for construction firms and employees, and will continue to provide economic benefits and opportunities into the future for ICBA members.</P>
<P>24. Large scale construction projects, such as those involved in the Project, are the lifeblood of the ICBA membership. ICBA members and their skilled workers are involved in virtually all major capital and infrastructure projects built in British Columbia.</P>
<P>25. To use a few examples: the approximately $3 billion Port Mann Bridge project was managed by an ICBA member, Peter Kiewit Sons, and Flatiron Constructors Canada. That project engaged over 100 sub-contractors, many of which were also ICBA members. Similarly, the approximately $2 billion Canada Line SkyTrain construction project involved over 400 supply and construction contracts, many of which were given to ICBA members.</P>
<P>26. Like these other large scale construction projects in the province, the ICBA expects that, over the life of the Project, a large number of contractors will obtain contracts or subcontracts on the Project, many of them members of the ICBA.</P>
<P>27. Given the unprecedented opportunities presented by the Project, the suspension, obstruction or cancellation of the project will have a direct and significant economic impact on many of the ICBA's members.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Proposed Intervention</TI>
<P>28. The ICBA represents a broad range of contractors within the construction industry of British Columbia and is an influential voice for legal and public policy advocacy and reform in the Province.</P>
<P>29. For the reasons set out above, many of the ICBA's members will be directly impacted by the appeal.</P>
<P>30. The ICBA has also participated as a party or intervenor in all levels of court and before various tribunals in a range of cases raising public law issues, including cases relating to privacy and freedom of information, labour relations and employment standards, challenges to tendering policies, freedom of expression and association in the workplace, and elections financing. See, for example: <CASEREF><SOC>Independent Contractors and Business Assn. of British Columbia v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>[1995] B.C.J. No. 777</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Vertex Construction Services v. International Union of Operating Engineers, Local 115</SOC><DOCKET>BCLRB No, B122/2000</DOCKET></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Advance Cutting &amp; Coring Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2001 SCC 70</CITE></CASEREF> (as a member of the Canadian Coalition of Open Shop Contracting Associations); <CASEREF><SOC>Daryl-Evans v. Empl. Standards</SOC><CITE>2002 BCSC 48</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Ledcor Industries Limited</SOC><CITE>2003 CIRB 216</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 213 v. Hochstein</SOC><CITE>2009 BCCA 355</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Allan v. British Columbia (Chief Electoral Officer)</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 1174</CITE></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Vander Zalm v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 1320</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Financial Institutions Commission (Re)</SOC><CITE>2013 BCIPC 2</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Construction and Specialized Workers Union, Local 1611 v. British Columbia (Information and Privacy Commissioner)</SOC><CITE>2015 BCSC 1471</CITE></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Office of the Superintendent of Pensions (Re)</SOC><CITE>2017 BCIPC 17</CITE></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>31. The ICBA is therefore in an ideal position to represent the community of contractors who would be significantly impacted by the outcome of this appeal, both in terms of the membership's ability to participate in the Project at issue, and in terms of any decision that could result in a less efficient and streamlined consultation process with respect to large-scale projects that impact the rights of First Nations.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Coalition Intervenors</TI>
<P>32. In the court below, the ICBA intervened jointly with the Progressive Contractors Association of Canada (&ldquo;<BOLD>PCA</BOLD>), the Canadian Iron, Steel and Industrial Workers' Union (&ldquo;<BOLD>CISIWU</BOLD>&rdquo;), and the Canada West Construction Union (&ldquo;<BOLD>CWCU</BOLD>&rdquo;) (collectively, the &ldquo;<BOLD>Coalition Intervenors</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>33. I have consulted with the other members of the Coalition Intervenors. Specifically, I have consulted with Paul de Jong of PCA, Francis W. Nolan of CISIWU, and Ken Baerg of CWCU.</P>
<P>34. The other members of the Coalition Intervenors also seek to intervene in the appeal of this matter and have authorized me to include their affidavits from the BC Supreme Court (Case No. S-173649) as exhibits to my affidavit, for the purpose of this application to intervene in the appeal.</P>
<P>35. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of Affidavit #1 of Paul de Jong, sworn on August 14, 2017.</P>
<P>36. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of Affidavit <BOLD>#1</BOLD> of Francis W. Nolan, made on July 25, 2017.</P>
<P>37. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of Affidavit #1 of Ken Baerg, made on August 9, 2017.</P>
<P>38. The Coalition Interveners have a common interest in ensuring that the Project (and others like it) proceed without delay or obstruction, and that any decision on appeal takes into account the importance of maintaining clear lines of jurisdictional authority with respect to government approval of large-scale construction and resource extraction projects.</P>
<P>39. If granted leave to intervene, the Coalition Intervenors will seek to avoid the duplication of submissions of the parties, and will limit their submissions and participation to that permitted by the Court.</P>
<P>40. I have read and confirm that the proposed legal submissions set out in the Coalition Intervenors' Memorandum of Argument on this application accurately reflect the position of the Coalition Intervenors in this appeal, and represent the position to be advanced by the Coalition Intervenors' counsel, subject to any necessary changes resulting from the arguments advanced by the parties or directions of the Court.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Late Filing of the Coalition Intervenor's Notice of Motion and Memorandum of Argument</UNDER></TI>
<P>41. The Coalition Intervenors were unable to file their application materials within the 14&mdash;day deadline, because of the timing of their receipt of the filed factum from the Appellants/Petitioners.</P>
<P>42. I am informed by counsel, and do verily believe, that our counsel received the filed factums of the Appellants/Petitioners and the Respondents in the appeal on December 27, 2018, from the Respondent Trans Mountain Pipeline ULC, and this was the first time our counsel was made aware that all of the parties factums had been filed on these dates.</P>
<P>43. The Appellants' factum had been filed on December 20, 2018, and both Respondents' factums had been filed on December 21, 2018. Under the Rules, the 14-day deadline for intervenor applications expired on January 3, 2019.</P>
<P>44. Due to the delay in receiving the filed materials, and holiday travel and vacations of the various representatives of the Coalition Intervenors and our legal counsel, we were unable to prepare the Coalition Intervenor's materials by January 3, 2019, which was the deadline under the Rules and have just been able to complete these materials now.</P>
<P>45. I am informed by our legal counsel that counsel for the Government Respondent h as consented to the late filing of our intervenor application.</P>
<P>46. I am also informed by our legal counsel that they contacted counsel for the Appellants/Petitioners and counsel for the Respondent Trans Mountain Pipeline ULC on January 21, 2019, to determine whether the parties would consent to the late filing of our intervenor application.</P>
<P>47. I am informed by our legal counsel that the Appellants/Petitioners' counsel advised that they were seeking instructions on the matter. At the of swearing this affi davit, we have not yet heard back from counsel for the Appellants/Petitioners.</P>
<P>48. I am also informed by our legal counsel that they have not heard back from counsel for the Respondent Trans Mountain on the matter.</P>
