<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">A. Request of an Extension of Time to File Application for Leave to Intervene</TI>
<P>1. At the outset, the Independent Contractors and Businesses Association (&ldquo;<BOLD>ICBA</BOLD>&rdquo;), the Progressive Contractors Association of Canada (&ldquo;<BOLD>PCA</BOLD>&rdquo;), the Canadian Iron, Steel and Industrial Workers' Union (&ldquo;<BOLD>CISIWU</BOLD>&rdquo;), and the Canada West Construction Union (&ldquo;<BOLD>CWCU</BOLD>&rdquo;) (collectively, the &ldquo;<BOLD>Coalition Intervenors</BOLD>&rdquo;) seek an extension pursuant to Rule 52 of the <EM>Court of Appeal Rules</EM>, B.C. Reg. 297/2001 to file their notice of motion and memorandum of argument.</P>
<P>2. The Coalition Intervenors were unable to file their application materials within the 14&mdash;day deadline, because of the timing of their receipt of the filed factum from the Petitioners/Appellants, and the holiday travel and vacations of the various representatives of the Coalition Intervenors, as well as their legal counsel.
<P1>Affidavit #1 of Christopher Gardner, made on January 21, 2019 (&ldquo;<BOLD>Gardner Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P1></P>
<P>3. Both the Government Respondent and Trans Mountain Respondent consent to the late&mdash;filing of the Coalition Intervenors' application for leave to intervene. The Petitioners/Appellants advise that they do not consent to the late filing of the Coalition Intervenors' application, nor will they actively oppose it.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">B. Overview of the Proposed Intervenors and its Interest in the Appeal</TI>
<P>4. The Coalition Intervenors seek leave to jointly intervene in this appeal, to file a factum, and to have the question of oral argument determined by the panel subsequently appointed to hear the appeal.</P>
<P>5. The ICBA was established in B.C. over forty years ago and is the oldest open shop organization in Canada. Representing more than 2,000 companies and clients, including over 1,000 construction companies, ICBA members and their skilled workers are involved in virtually all major capital and infrastructure projects built in British Columbia.</P>
<P>6. The ICBA advocates on behalf of free enterprise and the principle of open and fair bidding for projects, without discrimination on the basis of an employer's association with specific unions. ICBA is also the single largest sponsor of construction apprentices in BC and trains over 3,000 construction professionals annually.
<P1>Gardner Affidavit.</P1></P>
<P>7. The PCA represents approximately 115 construction companies with unionized workforces across Canada, including many in British Columbia.</P>
<P>8. It advocates in favour of sustainable economic development initiatives and reasonable regulatory reforms, and seeks to promote productive and collaborative labour-management relationships that serve both worker and employer interests.</P>
<P>9. To achieve these goals, it engages in public and industry-level advocacy on behalf of its members, and provides a range of advisory and educational services to its member companies.
<P1>Affidavit #1 of Paul de Jong, made on August 14, 2017 (&ldquo;<BOLD>de Jong Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P1></P>
<P>10. The two other organizations making up the Coalition Intervenors are trade unions: the Canadian Iron, Steel and Industrial Workers' Union (&ldquo;<BOLD>CISIWU</BOLD>&rdquo;), and Canada West Construction Union (&ldquo;<BOLD>CWCU</BOLD>&rdquo;), both of whom have collective bargaining relationships with construction companies that have an interest in participating in the Project.
<P1>Affidavit #1 of Ken Baerg, made August 9, 2017 (&ldquo;<BOLD>Baerg Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;), at paras 7&ndash;12;</P1>
<P1>Affidavit #1 of Francis W. Nolan, made July 25, 2017 (&ldquo;<BOLD>Nolan Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;), at paras 5, 8.</P1></P>
<P>11. The CISIWU and the CWCU represent thousands of members who work in the construction industry across British Columbia.
<P1>Baerg Affidavit, <EM>supra</EM> at paras 3&ndash;5, 7-8;</P1>
<P1>Nolan Affidavit, <EM>supra</EM> at para 8.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Direct Interest</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. The Coalition Intervenors have a direct interest in the appeal in terms of their interest in supporting and obtaining work on the Project itself.</P>
<P>13. If the relief sought in the appeal is granted, that would cause further and more extensive delays in moving the Project ahead, if not halting it altogether, which would cause direct harm to all of the members of the Coalition Intervenors.</P>
<P>14. Large scale construction ventures like the Project are of significant importance to the economic strength and prosperity of ICBA and PCA members in the construction industry.
<P1>Gardner Affidavit, <EM>supra</EM>;</P1>
<P1>de Jong Affidavit, <EM>supra</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>15. Therefore, the Project&mdash;estimated at approximately $7.4 billion dollars&mdash;represents an important economic opportunity for the companies represented by the ICBA and the PCA.
<P1>Gardner Affidavit, <EM>supra</EM>;</P1>
<P1>de Jong Affidavit, <EM>supra</EM>.</P1></P>
<P>16. The Project will also provide a large number of jobs for construction workers represented by the other Coalition Intervenors&mdash;CISIWU and CWCU.
<P1>Baerg Affidavit, <EM>supra</EM> at paras 7&ndash;12;</P1>
<P1>Nolan Affidavit, <EM>supra</EM> at paras 7&ndash;13.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Public Interest</UNDER></TI>
<P>17. Equally important from the perspective of the Coalition Intervenors is the broader public law principles at stake in this proceeding, and its potential impact on the ability of governments to support construction and resource extraction projects without undue delay.</P>
<P>18. The Petitioners/Appellants allege that in approving the Project, the provincial Crown failed to fulfil its duty to consult the Petitioners/Appellants.</P>
<P>19. In the Federal Court of Appeal, the Petitioners/Appellants&mdash;along with many other First Nations and other stakeholders who may be impacted by the Project&mdash;made essentially an identical claim against the federal government with respect to the federal approval of the same project. The Federal Court of Appeal rules that additional consultation by the Federal Govern ment with First Nations groups was required in order to fulfill the duty to consult. That additional federal consultation is underway.</P>
<P>20. In granting the certificate, the provincial government relied heavily on the consultation processes and procedures undertaken by the federal government, given the federal government's primary responsibility over the regulation and approval of interprovincial pipelines.</P>
<P>21. The provincial government cannot lawfully obstruct the Project, given the federal government's primary constitutional responsibility over interprovincial pipelines. As a result, the provincial government must follow the federal lead on this matter.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Campbell-Bennett v. Comstock Midwestern Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1954] SCR 207</CITE></CASEREF>;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Westcoast Energy Inc. v. Canada (National Energy Board)</SOC><CITE>[1998] 1 SCR 322</CITE></CASEREF>;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Burnaby (City) v. Trans Mountain Pipeline ULC</SOC><CITE>2015 BCSC 2140</CITE><PARANUM>60</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>2017 BCCA 132</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>22. From the Coalition Intervenors' perspective, it is important that the jurisdictional lines with respect to the approval of such projects be maintained, in order to promote consultations with the appropriate government authority and to avoid the risk of undue delay and inefficiency in the approval process.</P>
<P>23. While fully supporting the importance of the Crown fulfilling its constitutional obligations to the Petitioners/Appellants, it is also important that the protection of aboriginal rights does not result in a means by which large scale projects can be effecti vely paralyzed by overlapping consultation processes and court challenges.</P>
<P>24. Maintaining clear jurisdictional lines, and therefore clear lines of responsibility in terms of the duty to consult, is particularly important in large scale, cross-jurisdictional projects which may impact many First Nations groups.</P>
<P>25. If both levels of government owe a duty to consult with every group impacted with respect to the approval of a single project, the duplicative consultation processes and subsequent court challenges in multiple jurisdictions could represent an undue obstruction to project approvals with no benefit in terms of the quality or meaningfulness of the consultation.</P>
<P>26. The risk of overlapping duties to consult across multiple jurisdictions&mdash;and subsequently overlapping and potentially conflicting court proceedings and remedies&mdash;is of serious concern to the Coalition Intervenors and others who depend on resource extraction and project construction for jobs and economic prosperity.</P>
<P>27. This appeal therefore raises important public law issues of significance to the Coalition Intervenors, and the public at large, which may result in the blurring of the division of powers with respect to ultimate responsibility over the approval of interprovincial pipeline projects and obligations to First Nations communities.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">C. Legal Test to be Applied</TI>
<P>28. An order granting leave to intervene in an appeal is discr etionary, and may be made on any terms and conditions the Court considers appropriate. This Court may grant leave to intervene in circumstances where:
<P1>i. A party has a direct interest in an appeal; or</P1>
<P1>ii. The appeal raises public law issues that legitimately engage the applicant's interests, and the applicant brings a different and useful perspective to those issues that will be of assistance to the Court.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Carter v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2012 BCCA 502</CITE><PARANUM>11&ndash;13</PARANUM></CASEREF>;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>J.I. Properties Inc. v. PPG Architectural Coatings Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2015 BCCA 240</CITE><COURTJUR>Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 14.</P1></P>
<P>29. The Coalition Intervenors have a direct interest in the outcome of this appeal and can make a valuable contribution to the important public law issues raised in this appeal in light of their unique perspective.</P>
<P>30. As set out above, the Coalition Intervenors have a direct interest in the ability of their members to have an opportunity to obtain work on the Project that the appeal is attempting to hal t or delay.</P>
<P>31. If the Petitioners/Appellants are successful, the Court's decision will likely have a direct and prejudicial effect on the economic interests of the members of the Coalition Intervenors, all of whom will lose the opportunity to obtain economic benefits arising out of participation in the $7.4 billion project.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Garcia v. Tahoe Resources Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 320</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF>;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Faculty Association of the University of British Columbia v. University of British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2008 BCCA 376</CITE><PARANUM>7</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1></P>
<P>32. The Coalition Intervenors have a further legitimate and direct interest in the public law issues raised by the Petitioners/Appellants' claim, particularly in terms of e nsuring clear jurisdictional lines for the approval of large scale resource extraction and construction projects.</P>
<P>33. It is critically important to the Coalition Intervenors&mdash;unions, businesses, and associations alike&mdash;that environmental approval and consultation processes with First Nations be undertaken by the level of government with the final constitutional authority over those approvals and consultations.</P>
<P>34. This would recognize and ensure clear lines of authority with respect to consultation procedures, and avoid encouraging parties to raise substantively similar claims in parallel proceedings in two different jurisdictions with respect to the same project.</P>
<P>35. From the perspective of the Petitioners/Appellants, who assert that they have not been adequately consulted and their constitutional interests not adequately protected, raising claims against both levels of government is understandable, as it would best ensure that the Project does not move forward until adequate consultation has been undertaken.</P>
<P>36. However, from the perspective of maintaining the constitutional division of powers and ensuring the economical use of judicial resources, substantively duplicative proceedings in federal and provincial courts with respect to the approval of a single project risk blurring jurisdictional lines and causing undue and unnecessary delay.</P>
<P>37. Indeed, it is respectfully submitted that in the long run, dueling consultation procedures would promote uncertain lines of authority over the approval of construction and resource extraction projects.</P>
<P>38. This could encourage levels of government to interfere with projects beyond their jurisdiction, or seek to diminish their own responsibility to fulfill the duty to consult regarding those projects over which they have final authority.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">D. Summary of Proposed Submissions</TI>
<P>39. If permitted leave to intervene in the appeal, the Coalition Intervenors propose to make the following submissions, subject to revision based on the arguments of the parties and any orders of this Court:
<P1>iii. Efficiency and timeliness in the approval of large scale resource extraction and construction projects is important to the construction community and others who depend on such projects for economic growth and jobs, such as the Coalition Intervenors;</P1>
<P1>iv. The Coalition Intervenors fully acknowledge and accept the constitutional significance of aboriginal rights and appropriate consultation by the Crown, and recognize that meaningful consultation and accommodation necessarily may delay or, in some circumstances, even prevent certain forms of development;</P1>
<P1>v. However, the Coalition Intervenors intend to submit that the legal principles and requirements in this area should be designed to ensure that consultation takes place as efficiently as possible and with clear lines of jurisdictional authority over the approval of large scale projects;</P1>
<P1>vi. In this context, promoting efficiency and clear jurisdictional lines means that the duty to consult should be concentrated in the body with the primary jurisdiction to approve interprovincial pipelines, i.e., th<EM>e federal</EM> Crown, otherwise it could lead to conflicting government or court decisions with respect to approval;</P1>
<P1>vii. The Petitioners/Appellants are seeking relief against both the pr ovince and the federal government with respect to two different approvals for the same project;</P1>
<P1>viii. The federal government has the ultimate authority over the Project, and therefore even if the province disagrees, the federal government's decision to ap prove or not approve the Project will prevail;</P1>
<P1>ix. It follows that the province necessarily has to rely on the adequacy of the federal government's consultation in terms of whether to approve the Project;</P1>
<P1>x. As a result, the party with the real power to affect the interests of the Petitioners/Appellants is the federal government. The Petitioners/Appellants successfully challenged the adequacy of consultation by the federal government in the Federal Court of Appeal, resulting in additional consultation by the federal government;</P1>
<P1>xi. The federal government is currently undertaking additional consultation, which addresses the deficiencies identified by the Federal Court of Appeal;</P1>
<P1>xii. This appeal challenging the provincial government's decision therefore serves no valid legal purpose, given that the province has no power to halt or obstruct the Project;</P1>
<P1>xiii. And as the Supreme Court of Canada has recently decided, the Crown's duty to consult can be fulfilled by other state actors that have the power to make the &ldquo;final decision&rdquo; over a project, so long as the process &ldquo;affords an appropriate level of consultation to the affected Indigenous group&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Clyde River (Hamlet) v. Petroleum Geo-Services Inc.</SOC><CITE>2017 SCC 40</CITE><PARANUM>29&ndash;31, 39</PARANUM></CASEREF>;</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Chippewas of the Thames First Nation v. Enbridge Pipelines Inc.</SOC><CITE>2017 SCC 41</CITE><PARANUM>31-32, 37, 44</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P1>
<P1>xiv. In this case, federal consultation conducted primarily through the NEB was the appropriate mechanism to fulfil the Crown's duty to consult, given the federal government's power to make the &ldquo;final decision&rdquo; with respect to the Project;</P1>
<P1>xv. To the extent that Coastal First Nationals could be interpreted by requiring that the federal and provincial governments are required to maintain separate and independent consultation processes, this interpretation would be an error which could have adverse consequences which are neither required by nor consistent with constitutional principles;</P1>
<P1>xvi. In summary, the Coalition Intervenors will respectfully submit that the court should deny this appeal on the basis that:
<P2>a. the Petitioners/Appellants' real, substantive constitutional interests have been adjudicated in the federal jurisdiction because of the federal government's exclusive power over the ultimate approval of the Project;</P2>
<P2>b. the Petitioners/Appellants' position and constitutional interests have been adequately protected in the Federal Court of Appeal proceedings in adjudicating the sufficiency of federal consultation; and</P2>
<P2>c. duplicative consultations and overlapping proceedings unnecessarily increase costs and delay, and risk conflicting decisions on approval by two different orders of government as well as conflicting court decisions, even though only one level of government has the authority to make a &ldquo;final decision&rdquo; with respect to the Project.</P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">E. The Submissions of the Proposed Intervenors will be Useful and Different from those of the Other Parties</TI>
<P>40. In advancing the above positions, the Coalition Intervenors will be providing a useful and unique perspective not otherwise represented in this appeal&mdash;namely, that of key businesses and a broad segment of the workforce who expect to obtain work on the Project&mdash;and will advance arguments that will be of assistance to the Court in terms of understanding the broader impact of t he relief sought by the Petitioners/Appellants, and the legal basis advanced in support of that relief.</P>
<P>41. More specifically, the Coalition Intervenors are in an ideal position to make submissions on the importance of ensuring clear jurisdictional lines with respect to the approval of large-scale resource extraction and construction projects, while at the same time ensuring that the rights of the claimants will be adequately safeguarded in the parallel proceedings.</P>
<P>42. The participation of the Coalition Intervenors will not expand the scope of the proceedings or prejudice any of the parties, and efforts will be made to ensure that the submissions of the Coalition Intervenors will not duplicate those submissions made by t he parties to this appeal.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">F. Orders Sought</TI>
<P>43. For the reasons set out above, the Coalition Intervenors respectfully request:
<P1>a. That it be granted leave to intervene in this appeal;</P1>
<P1>b. That it be permitted to file a factum of no more than 20 pages on or before a date to be specified by the Court;</P1>
<P1>c. That it be granted permission to apply to the panel hearing the appeal for leave to prevent oral argument; and</P1>
<P1>d. That there shall be costs of this application or costs of the appeal awarded for or against the Coalition Intervenors.</P1></P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>Dated: January 24, 2019</P>
<P>&ellip35; Peter A. Gall, Q.C.</P>
<P>Counsel for the Coalition Intervenors</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
