<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>OVERVIEW</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The appellants, Squamish Nation (&ldquo;<BOLD>Squamish</BOLD>&rdquo;) make the following submissions with respect to the Independent Contractors and Business Association, the Progressive Contactors Association of Canada, the Canadian Iron, Steel and Industrial Workers' Union, and the Canada West Construction Union (collectively the &ldquo;<BOLD>intervenors</BOLD>&rdquo;) application to intervene, and extension of the filing period for the application:</P>
<P>2. The appellants:
<P1>a) take no position on the application seeking an extension to file the application for leave to intervene, subject to there being no delay in the hearing of the appeal; and</P1>
<P1>b) oppose the application of the intervenors seeking leave to intervene.</P1></P>
<P>3. The appellants oppose the intervenors' application to intervene on the grounds that they do not meet the grounds for intervention. The intervenors:
<P1>a) do not have a direct interest in the appeal; and</P1>
<P1>b) do not meet the requirements of a public interest intervenor because they will not bring a different and useful perspective to the issues on appeal that will be of assistance to the court.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>THE SQUAMISH APPEAL</UNDER></TI>
<P>4. Squamish is appealing an order of the British Columbia Supreme Court that found that the Province had adequately consulted the appellants prior to issuing an Environmental Assessment Certificate (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Certificate</BOLD>&rdquo;) for the Trans Mountain Expansion Project (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Project</BOLD>&rdquo;). This matter has been set down for hearing on April 10, 2019 for 1.5 days.</P>
<P>5. The appellants have submitted on the appeal that the Court below erred in determining:
<P1>a) that the Province was able to rely on the National Energy Board (the &ldquo;<BOLD>NEB</BOLD>&rdquo;) report as an equivalent assessment report for the Project;</P1>
<P1>b) that the adequate consultation did not and, constitutionally, could not require the Province to fill information gaps (or consult about filling perceived gaps) in the NEB assessment before deciding whether to issue a provincial Certificate;</P1>
<P1>c) that the Province did not have an obligation to consult with Squamish on the Province's change in position from the NEB process on the adequacy of the information on Project-related spills; and</P1>
<P1>d) that the Province was constitutionally constrained with respect to its obligations to consult and accommodate Squamish and by failing to find that the Province had an obligation to explain those constraints to Squamish.</P1></P>
<P>6. The appellants also submit in their appeal factum that, the NEB report having been set-aside as flawed by the Federal Court of Appeal in <UNDER><CASEREF><SOC>Tsleil-Waututh Nation v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2018 FCA 153</CITE></CASEREF></UNDER>, there is no longer a legal foundation for the provincial Certificate that purported to rely on the NEB report,</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI><UNDER>SUBMISSIONS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><N>1.</N><TI>Legal test for interventions</TI>
<P>7. An order granting intervenor status is discretionary and can be granted where the intervenor has (1) a direct interest in the litigation, in the sense that the result of the appeal will directly affect its legal rights or impose on it some additional legal obligation with a direct prejudicial effect or where (2) the appeal raises public interest issues that legitimately engage the applicant's interests, and the applicant brings a different and useful perspective to those issues that will be of assistance in resolving them.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Carter v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2012 BCCA 502</CITE><PARANUM>12-13</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>2.</N><TI>The intervenors do not have a direct interest</TI>
<P>8. The intervenors assert they have a direct interest in the litigation due to the potential they may secure contracts associated with the proposed Project.</P>
<P>9. The intervenors do not have a direct interest in this litigation as that term has been defined and applied by the Court of Appeal in intervention proceedings.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ahousaht Indian Band v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2012 BCCA 330</CITE><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>aff'd</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>2012 BCCA 404</CITE><PARANUM>4, 7, 8</PARANUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>; <UNDER><EM>Carter</EM></UNDER>, paras. 12-13</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The rights of the intervenors are not before the court in this proceeding. There are no binding contracts or employment opportunities regarding the Project in evidence.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Christopher Gardner made January 21, 2019, para. 19</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Even if contracts existed, those contracts would not be the subject of any order of the Court of Appeal in this proceeding.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>3.</N><TI>The intervenors' submissions will be of no assistance</TI>
<P>10. The intervenors submissions will not be of assistance to resolving the issues in this appeal The intervenors have proposed to intervene before the Court of Appeal on the same terms as were sought in the petition proceeding.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Jill Hamilton made January 31, 2019, Ex. &ldquo;A&rdquo;, para. 32; <EM>cf.</EM> Applicants' Memorandum of Argument, para. 39</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In the petition below the Applicant's submissions were not referenced in the decision or engaged with by the Court.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><UNDER><CASEREF><SOC>Squamish Nation v. British Columbia (Environment)</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 844</CITE></CASEREF></UNDER></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>Dated at the City of North Vancouver, Province of British Columbia, this 31st day of January, 2019.</P>
<P>&ellip35; F. Matthew Kirchner</P>
<P>Counsel for the Appellants</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
